{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}} {{Use British English|date=November 2015}} '''Frank Greenaway''' (9 July 1917 – 16 June 2013) was Keeper of [[Chemistry]] at the [[Science Museum (London)|Science Museum]] in [[London]], [[England]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Robert Anderson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2013/jul/16/frank-greenaway |title=Frank Greenaway obituary &#124; Culture |publisher=The Guardian |date= 16 July 2013|accessdate=2013-07-17 |location=London}}</ref> He authored a number of books and papers on the [[history of chemistry]].<ref>Frank Greenaway, ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=UQtUqR-Mb44C Chymica Acta: An Autobiographical Memoir]'', [[Jeremy Mills Publishing]], 2007. Autobiography/Festschrift. Contributors: Frank Greenaway, [[Robert Anderson (museum director)|Robert Anderson]], [[Peter J.T. Morris]], [[Derek Robinson (curator)|Derek Robinson]]. {{ISBN|978-1-905217-50-2}}. Launched at a [http://www.ambix.org/SHAC_Events_Chymica_Acta.htm meeting] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20081006120720/http://www.ambix.org/SHAC_Events_Chymica_Acta.htm |date=6 October 2008 }} of the [[Society for the History of Alchemy and Chemistry]] held at the [[Museum of the History of Science]] in [[Oxford]] on 10 December 2007.</ref>
Frank Greenaway studied Chemistry at [[Jesus College, Oxford|Jesus College]], [[University of Oxford|Oxford]]. He was invalided out of the [[World War II|War]] and subsequently taught in [[Bournemouth]], where he met his wife, Miranda (1916–2008). They had four children.
Greenaway lived in [[Surrey]] for most of his career as a [[curator]] at the Science Museum in London and a leading [[History of science|historian of science]], specializing in chemistry. He retired to [[Reading, Berkshire]].
