{{Portal|Ancient Near East}}
'''Maryannu''' is an ancient word for the caste of [[chariot]]-mounted hereditary warrior nobility which existed in many of the societies of the [[Middle East]] during the [[Bronze Age]].

The term is attested in the [[Amarna letters]] written by [[Haapi]]. [[Robert Drews]] writes that the name 'maryannu' although plural takes the singular 'marya', which in [[Sanskrit]] means "young warrior", and attaches a [[Hurrian]] suffix. (Drews:p.&nbsp;59)[https://books.google.com/books?id=fcVIcaJxgdUC&pg=PA59&vq=maryannu&dq=new+light+on+the+maryannu+as+chariot-warriors&lr=&source=gbs_search_s&sig=ACfU3U0DRvQBDUE0BwsKAzkQ7MPcz-ipfA] He suggests that at the beginning of the Late Bronze Age most would have spoken either Hurrian or [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan]] but by the end of the 14th century most of the Levant maryannu had [[Semitic languages|Semitic]] names.

